1. Introduction & Setup

•	JavaScript (JS): A programming language used to make websites interactive (e.g., responding to clicks, fetching data).

•	Linking JS:
  o	External: Create a .js file and link it in your HTML:
      HTML
      <script src="index.js"></script>
  o	Location: Best practice is to place the <script> tag at the very bottom of the <body> so HTML loads before the script runs.

•	Output:
  o	console.log("Hello"); - Prints to the developer console (Inspect -> Console).
  o	window.alert("Hello"); - Creates a popup alert.

________________________________________

2. Variables & Data Types

•	Variables: Containers for storing data.
  o	let: variable that can be changed later. (Block scoped).
  o	const: variable that cannot be changed (Constant).
  o	var: old way, generally avoided now. (Function scoped).
  o	Example: let age = 25; const pi = 3.14;

•	Data Types:
  o	String: Text, defined with quotes. "Hello" or 'Hello'.
  o	Number: Integers (10) or decimals (10.5).
  o	Boolean: true or false.
  o	Null: Intentional absence of any object value.
  o	Undefined: A variable that has been declared but not assigned a value.

•	Template Literals: Using backticks (`) allows you to embed variables directly into strings.
    JavaScript
    let name = "Bro";
    console.log(`Hello ${name}!`); // Output: Hello Bro!

________________________________________

3. User Input & Type Conversion

•	Window Prompt: let username = window.prompt("What's your name?");

•	HTML Input: Getting value from a textbox (more common).
    JavaScript
    let username = document.getElementById("myText").value;

•	Type Conversion: User input is often a string by default. You must convert it to do math.
  o	Number(age): Converts string "25" to number 25.
  o	String(age): Converts number to string.
  o	Boolean(value): Converts to true/false.

________________________________________

4. Control Flow (Logic)

•	If Statements: Basic logic.
    JavaScript
    if (age >= 18) {
        console.log("You are an adult");
    } else {
        console.log("You are a child");
    }

•	Ternary Operator: A shortcut for if/else.
  o	condition ? valueIfTrue : valueIfFalse
  o	let message = age >= 18 ? "Adult" : "Minor";

•	Switch Statement: Better than many else if statements when checking one variable against many values.

•	Loops:
  o	While Loop: Repeats while a condition is true.
  o	For Loop: Repeats a specific number of times. for(let i = 0; i < 10; i++).

________________________________________

5. Arrays & Functions

•	Arrays: Lists of items. let fruits = ["apple", "orange", "banana"];
  o	push(): Add to end.
  o	pop(): Remove from end.
  o	unshift(): Add to beginning.
  o	shift(): Remove from beginning.

•	Functions: Reusable blocks of code.
    JavaScript
    function happyBirthday(name, age){
        console.log(`Happy birthday ${name}`);
    }

•	Arrow Functions: A shorter syntax for functions.
    JavaScript
    const greeting = (name) => console.log(`Hello ${name}`);

•	Array Methods (Advanced):
  o	.map(): Creates a new array by applying a function to every element.
  o	.filter(): Creates a new array with all elements that pass a test.
  o	.reduce(): Reduces an array to a single value (e.g., summing numbers).

________________________________________

6. Objects & Classes

•	Object: A collection of related properties and methods.
    JavaScript
    const person = {
        firstName: "Spongebob",
        lastName: "Squarepants",
        age: 30,
        sayHello: function(){ console.log("Hi!") }
    };

•	this keyword: Refers to the object where the code is currently running. In the example above, this.firstName would find "Spongebob".

•	Classes: Blueprints for creating objects.
    JavaScript
    class Player {
        constructor(name, score){
            this.name = name;
            this.score = score;
        }
    }

________________________________________

7. DOM Manipulation (Crucial for Websites)

•	DOM (Document Object Model): Representation of the page that JS can change.

•	Selectors:
  o	document.getElementById("myId")
  o	document.querySelector(".myClass") (Selects the first match)
  o	document.querySelectorAll(".myClass") (Selects all matches)

•	Event Listeners: Waiting for user interaction.
    JavaScript
    let button = document.getElementById("myBtn");
    button.addEventListener("click", function(){
        alert("Button clicked!");
    });

•	ClassList: Easily add/remove CSS classes from JS.
  o	element.classList.add("active");
  o	element.classList.remove("active");
  o	element.classList.toggle("active");

________________________________________

8. Advanced Topics (Async/Await & Fetch)

•	Asynchronous Code: Code that runs out of order (doesn't stop the rest of the program).

•	Callbacks: A function passed as an argument to another function (e.g., "Do this after you finish loading").

•	Promises: An object that promises to return a value in the future (either resolved or rejected).

•	Async / Await: The modern, cleaner way to handle promises.

•	Fetch API: Used to get data from servers (APIs).
    JavaScript
    async function getData() {
        try {
            const response = await fetch("https://api.example.com/data");
            if(!response.ok) throw new Error("Could not fetch resource");
            const data = await response.json();
            console.log(data);
        } catch(error) {
            console.error(error);
        }
    }
